 for themselves and their family in the event of pandemic influenza.\n</p><!--fig ft0--><!--fig mode=article f1--><div class="fig iconblock whole_rhythm clearfix" id="Fig1" co-legend-rid="lgnd_Fig1"><a href="/pmc/articles/PMC2556339/figure/Fig1/" target="figure" rid-figpopup="Fig1" rid-ob="ob-Fig1"><!--fig/graphic|fig/alternatives/graphic mode="anchored" m1--><div data-largeobj="" data-largeobj-link-rid="largeobj_idm139996309224608" class="figure"><img class="fig-image" alt="An external file that holds a picture, illustration, etc.&#10;Object name is 12879_2008_Article_708_Fig1_HTML.jpg" title="An external file that holds a picture, illustration, etc.&#10;Object name is 12879_2008_Article_708_Fig1_HTML.jpg" src="/pmc/articles/PMC2556339/bin/12879_2008_Article_708_Fig1_HTML.jpg" /></div><div id="largeobj_idm139996309224608" class="largeobj-link align_right" style="display: none"><a target="object" href="/pmc/articles/PMC2556339/figure/Fig1/?report=objectonly">Open in a separate window</a></div></a><div class="icnblk_cntnt" id="lgnd_Fig1"><div><a class="figpopup" href="/pmc/articles/PMC2556339/figure/Fig1/" target="figure" rid-figpopup="Fig1" rid-ob="ob-Fig1">Figure 1</a></div><!--caption a7--><div class="caption"><p id="__p130">\n<strong>Prevalence estimates and 95% confidence intervals for response combinations to the three questions on perceived threat for pandemic influenza</strong>. Source: New South Wales Health Survey Program. Sydney: New South Wales Department of Health, 2008.</p></div></div></div><p id="__p131">Table <a href="/pmc/articles/PMC2556339/table/Tab4/" target="table" class="fig-table-link figpopup" rid-figpopup="Tab4" rid-ob="ob-Tab4" co-legend-rid=""><span style="position: relative;text-decoration:none;">&#x200B;<span class="figpopup-sensitive-area" style="left: -2.5em;">Table4</span></span><span>4</span></a> also shows the combined indicators pandemic influenza likely and concern for self and family as well as pandemic influenza likely and concern for self and family and changed life by sex, age group, demographic characteristics, and the indicators of level of psychological distress and general self-rated health status.</p><p id="__p132">Table <a href="/pmc/articles/PMC2556339/table/Tab5/" target="table" class="fig-table-link figpopup" rid-figpopup="Tab5" rid-ob="ob-Tab5" co-legend-rid=""><span style="position: relative;text-decoration:none;">&#x200B;<span class="figpopup-sensitive-area" style="left: -2.5em;">Table5</span></span><span>5</span></a> shows the indicators willing to receive vaccination, isolate themselves, or wear a face mask by sex, age group, demographic characteristics, and the indicators of level of psychological distress and general self-rated health status. Overall, the majority of the population would be willing to receive vaccination (75.4%), willing to be isolated (70.2%), and willing to wear a mask (59.9%), if pandemic influenza were to occur.\n</p><!--table ft1--><!--table-wrap mode="anchored" t5--><div class="table-wrap table anchored whole_rhythm" id="Tab5"><h3>Table 5</h3><!--caption a7--><div class="caption"><p id="__p133">Prevalence estimates and pairwise comparisons, willingness to comply with health protective behaviours, by socio-demographic subgroups and health status</p></div><div data-largeobj="" data-largeobj-link-rid="largeobj_idm139996305657616" class="xtable"><table frame="hsides" rules="groups" class="rendered small default_table"><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Population</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Very willing to comply with vaccination</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Very willing to comply with isolation</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Very willing to comply with wearing a face mask</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Very willing to comply with ALL: vaccination + isolation+ wearing a face mask</th></tr><tr><th rowspan="1" colspan="1"></th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">% 